canonical:
  title: 大駕
  author: 卞季良
  language: lzh
  text: 龍御當陽儼臨區宇鸞輿幸北聿觀神都凡在見聞疇非蹈舞欽惟聦明齊舜文思協堯就二帝之舊封式新大邑登三王之至治克配皇天視前古而增光罄幅員以稱慶梯航相繼草木擧欣伏念臣猥以庸資幸逢煕運迹拘海甸班雖阻於駿犇心注雲霄誠倍殫於虎拜
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 大駕
  author: 卞季良
  language: lzh
  text: 龍御當陽。儼臨區宇。鸞輿幸北。聿觀神都。凡在見聞。疇非蹈舞。欽惟聦明齊舜。文思協堯。就二帝之舊封。式新大邑。登三王之至治。克配皇天。視前古而增光。罄幅員以稱慶。梯航相繼。草木擧欣。伏念臣猥以庸資。幸逢煕運。迹拘海甸。班雖阻於駿犇。心注雲霄。誠倍殫於虎拜。
korean:
  title: 대가
  author: 변계량
  language: kor
  text: 용어(龍御)가 남면(南面)하시어 엄연히 천하에 군림(君臨)하시고, 난여(鸞輿)가 북행(北幸)하시어 비로소 신도(神都)를 보옵시니, 무릇 보고 듣는 자 뉘 아니 기뻐 춤추오리이까. 공경히 생각하옵건대, 총명이 순(舜) 임금과 같으시고 문사(文思) 하심이 요(堯) 임금과 맞으시어, 이제(二帝)의 옛날 봉읍(封邑)에 나가 새로 큰 도읍을 만드시고, 삼왕(三王)의 지극한 정치에 올라 바로 황천(皇天)에 짝하옵시니, 전고(前古)에 비하여 빛을 더하고 온 세계를 통하여 경사로 여겨서 제항(梯航)이 서로 꼬리를 물고 초목(草木)이 모두 기뻐하옵나이다. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 신(臣)이 외람되게 용렬한 자질(資質)로 다행히 희운(熙運)을 만나, 몸이 해전(海甸)에 구애되어 준분(駿奔)의 반열(班列)에 참가하지는 못하오나, 마음은 운소(雲宵)에 쏠려 호배(虎拜)보다 정성을 곱절로 다하옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0350_010_0630&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: The Imperial Procession
  author: Byeon Gyeyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The dragon-drawn chariot turns southward, commanding all lands with solemn majesty,
    While the phoenix carriage journeys north to behold the sacred capital at last.
    All who witness and hear cannot help but dance with joy.

    I reverently contemplate: Your wisdom matches that of sage Shun,
    Your literary grace harmonizes with the brilliance of Yao.
    You venture forth to the ancient domains of the Two Emperors
    And establish a new great city;
    You ascend to the supreme governance of the Three Sovereigns
    And stand equal with Heaven itself.
    Your glory surpasses all antiquity,
    And the four corners of the world rejoice together.
    The roads of commerce stretch unbroken,
    And all grass and trees celebrate.

    Yet I, your humble servant, of mediocre talent,
    Fortunate to live in this blessed age,
    Am bound to these coastal lands,
    Unable to join the ranks of those who ride in swift attendance.
    Still, my heart soars toward the heavens above,
    And my devotion surpasses even the most fervent prostration.
  footnotes:
    - The Two Emperors (二帝) refers to Yao and Shun, legendary sage-kings of ancient China
    - The Three Sovereigns (三王) refers to Yu, Yin, and Zhou, the three dynasties that established ideal governance
    - The poem is addressed to a royal figure, likely celebrating an imperial progress or relocation of the capital
